post_text:
In an effort to help families and students during the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic, the USDA is making school meals FREE to all JPS students for the remainder of the fall semester (through December 18).

All students enrolled at Jenks Public Schools ‚Äì whether attending at-school or taking classes online through the Trojan Connect Program ‚Äì can eat for FREE!

Students in school can simply go to their site cafeteria for a free meal.

Students enrolled in Trojan Connect may pick up a free meal on the north side of the Central Campus Dining Hall each weekday between 11:30 a.m. and 12:30 p.m.

Milk will be available a la carte at elementary and intermediate sites. Students at Jenks Middle School and Jenks High School may purchase a second entree and drinks a la carte. All a la carte purchases must be paid for with cash or from money in student meal accounts.

Meals will not be served when school is closed due to inclement weather

Menus can be viewed here http://www.schoolnutritionandfitness.com/index.php?sid=1501646811237&page=menus

We made it.

Alright, so maybe there won't be the usual sights and sounds of a first day of school, but it's still a milestone in the lives of our students. Some may be at the beginning of their JPS journey, others have arrived at their final year. Under these and any other circumstances, we are thrilled to welcome students to a new school year. Huge thanks to our teachers and staff members for their monumental efforts in preparing for distance and virtual learning!

***IMPORTANT UPDATE FOR JPS PARENTS/GUARDIANS:***

With new recommendations published last week from the Oklahoma State Department of Education and the Oklahoma State Department of Health, the deadline to opt-in to the Trojan Connect Program (virtual option) or the blended option has been extended from July 31 to August 7.

This extension allows more time for JPS parents/guardians to make an informed decision about the best option for their student(s) and family, and also allows JPS administrators more time to monitor the recent rise in COVID-19 cases and update the return to learn plan accordingly. More information will be shared after the JPS Board of Education meeting on Monday, August 3.

Visit www.jenksps.org for details on all of JPS' return to learn options.

post_text:
JPS Families, We want to thank you for your patience and support as we have been working on the issues with Registration Gateway and the Back to School online process. We have been working with the company and believe the issues of which we are aware have been fixed.

Here are a couple of tips to try if you have been having trouble:

1. Shut down and restart your computer to clear the cache.

2. If you add a student to your Parent Portal account, wait until the next day to try to complete the online forms. Our data exchange happens during the night and so the student you added won't show up until this happens.

If you continue to have problems completing the online forms, please submit a ticket here: https://jenksps.co1.qualtrics.com/jfe/form/SV_8BmvW9ayAYmfeCx and someone will contact you.

If you have questions or would like to request virtual/blended classes (Trojan Connect) for the 2020-2021 school year, that is a different form that can be found here: https://www.jenksps.org/vnews/display.v/ART/5f0f0a8c927dc

post_text: Maya Lehwald had no idea what was happening when Jenks Public Schools' police officers and a caravan of cars pulled up to her house this morning. She was thrilled to learn she has been named the 2019-20 Outstanding AAA School Safety Patroller of the Year by AAA Oklahoma! As a School Safety Patroller, Maya helped her classmates at Jenks East Elementary to keep control and maintain safety expectations. She also demonstrated leadership and characteristics of a stand-up citizen while serving her school. Maya was nominated by her teachers and selected by AAA Oklahoma for this prestigious honor! Congrats!

For 25 years, the Mr. & Miss JHS program has been part of the "tradition of excellence" at Jenks High School.

Every single one of these seniors - nominees and finalists - are phenonemal examples of what it means to be a Trojan. Their character, determination, work ethic, compassion, and drive to succeed will carry on the tradition of excellence many years into the future.

The faculty and staff members at JHS are so proud of all these students have accomplished. A video is no subsitute for the real ceremony, but under the circumstances, it is a privilege to recognize these men and women for who they are, and for who they will become.

Please enjoy the 2020 Mr. & Miss JHS Ceremony!

post_text:
UPDATE: The last day of school for the 2019-20 school year is Friday, May 15. The JPS Distance Learning Plan will run through Friday, May 15.

With the closure of all schools due to COVID-19, the Oklahoma State Department of Education (OSDE) is allowing districts to change the last of school. Based on guidance from the OSDE, the last day of instruction for all JPS students will be Friday, May 15.

Senior students and parents of senior students will receive an update today from Jenks High School with new information about plans for graduation and other senior events. At this time, the goal is to have some kind of virtual graduation on May 18 and a traditional graduation ceremony is TENTATIVELY scheduled for June 26. Please keep in mind, the safety and security of our students and staff members remains the top priority. This event can only take place if we are in compliance with federal, state, and local guidelines on social gatherings and social distancing.

post_text:
A GOLDEN DAY IN THE WATER.

The boys AND girls swimming teams captured 6A state championships tonight! The boys defended their title and claimed their third championship in the last four years, while the girls swam to the top of the podium for the first time since 2010. Jenks is the first school since 2014 to win boys and girls swimming titles in the same year. Congrats to these Trojans and their coaches!

post_text:
Students in the Jenks Middle School Global program are having the time of their lives in Greece!

While the Arts & Humanities class pushes south into the Peloponnese, the Science & Agriculture class is driving along the Aegean Sea north toward Thessaloniki (not far from the homeland of Alexander the Great).

Over the past couple days, students have learned about the Battle of Thermopylae, the history of olive production in Greece, experienced life in central and northern Greece, and witnessed some of the most majestic scenery in all the world.

post_text: She will always be viewed as a leader, a mentor, and an innovator. Everything she did was fueled by a love of students and a desire to see them succeed. Linda Reid is retiring tomorrow after seven and a half years as the Site Principal at Jenks East Intermediate and "thank you" doesn't quite seem sufficient for the contributions she made to her school and to the culture of this District. Throughout her career in education, Linda was a tireless advocate for students. She inspired with her attitude and motivated with her relentless enthusiasm. We will always be grateful for the mark she made on Jenks Public Schools. You will be missed, Linda. Congratulations on an exceptional career!

post_text: An incredible night at the Congressional Academy Nomination Ceremony, where students received their nomination from Congressman Hern to a United States service academy. Three Jenks students received their nomination tonight, and we could not be prouder of their amazing accomplishments. Isabella Griffey received a nomination to the United States Naval Academy, Hudson Mazzei got a nomination to the United States Military Academy, and Kevin Glynn earned a nomination to the United States Air Force Academy. Congratulations, Trojans!
